\f0\fs24 \cf0 Operating amplifiers\
\
An Operational Amplifier (commonly abbreviated as an Op-Amp) is a high-gain, direct-coupled, integrated electronic voltage amplifier characterized by two differential inputs and typically a single-ended output. Developed originally to perform mathematical operations (such as addition, subtraction, integration, and differentiation) in historical analog computers, the modern solid-state op-amp has evolved into the foundational building block of linear, non-linear, and radio-frequency analog signal processing circuits.The primary defining traits of an ideal op-amp include infinite input impedance (drawing zero current from input signals), zero output impedance (ensuring unattenuated voltage delivery to subsequent stages), and an exceptionally high Open-Loop Voltage Gain ($A_\{OL\}$).Because this open-loop gain is too massive and unstable for standalone applications, op-amps are almost universally implemented utilizing a Closed-Loop Negative Feedback system. By routing a portion of the output signal back to the inverting input through an external resistor network, the immense open-loop gain is precisely attenuated and stabilized. This closed-loop configuration enables the circuit to behave predictably according to the geometric ratio of its external passive components, making it indispensable for precise sensor signal amplification, voltage buffering, active filtering, and analog-to-digital interface conditioning.}